Locations of conservation areas

[List of conservation areas with maps and appraisals](https://www.rochdale.gov.uk/downloads/download/191/list-of-conservation-areas-maps-and-appraisals)

About applying for planning permission in a conservation area 
A conservation area is an area of special architectural or historical interest that it's desirable to protect or enhance.
If you're planning to make changes to your property and it's in a conservation area, you may need to apply for planning permission.
There are many conservation areas in the borough of Rochdale

#  Conservation areas 
A conservation area is an area of special architectural or historical interest or is desirable to protect or enhance.
Conservation areas protect historic buildings, gardens, trees, spaces and views so that area can then be passed on to future generations and protected from inappropriate development or demolition. [More about conservation areas from Historic England](https://historicengland.org.uk/advice/planning/conservation-areas/).

[See a full list of conservation areas in the borough of Rochdale](https://www.rochdale.gov.uk/heritage-conservation/conservation-areas).

About non-designated heritage assets 
Non-designated heritage assets are places we've identified as having some significance to the local heritage.
They make important contributions to the local distinctiveness, settlement formation, traditional character or history of the borough but don't meet the criteria for listed buildings.
Non-designated heritage assets can be buildings, monuments, sites, places, areas and landscapes.

About applying for listed building consent 
A listed building is a building or structure of special architectural or historic interest.
They're recognised by the government as needing protection from being demolished or changed.
Listed buildings can be churches, houses, bridges and gates.
  * [ **Next page** : Changes you need consent for  ](https://www.rochdale.gov.uk/planning-permission/apply-listed-building-consent/2)
